review.reviewBody:
I was looking for a more aggressive tread to take a gravel bike on singletrack without compromising efficiency to and from the trailhead. The Sendero doesn't disappoint! The siped side-knobs are amazing on loose and off-camber terrain, and the ramped center knobs roll like a continuous ridge on pavement. The 47mm width is perfect for mixed terrain. 

My only complaint is the bead is super tight on my wheels (using them with Ibis 733 Aluminum wheels). It took two guys, a broken lever, and lot of patience to get them back on there after patching a sidewall tear. Not a big deal. I love these tires. 

I'll definitely get them again!
review.name: Great grip and fast rolling

review.reviewBody: Night and day difference in comfort compared to alloy seat post. Softened my ride on gravel quite a bit.
review.name: Great upgrade

review.reviewBody:
At the time of the review, I've put in about 200 miles in on the seatpost.  It is installed with carbon grip paste into a Ritchey Road Logic at 5NM at the seatpost clamp.  No slipping issues, although that's more often related to the frame's tolerance.  

I've only had a few carbon seatposts over the years, I know they dampen vibration a little bit, depending on the length of seatpost showing.  I have about 13cm of carbon showing(excluding the head of the seatpost as that's aluminum) and it's noticeably less buzzy than an aluminum seatpost.  I'm riding a Ritchey Road Logic, a steel bike, so the vibration is stronger than most carbon frames, but this little bit of carbon helps to smooth out the rear end a little bit.  

The adjusting bolts are a little stiff at first as the threads on two bolts are blue threadlocked, but as you adjust them, the threadlocker loosens up a bit and the adjusting becomes easier.  It can be slightly difficult to adjust as you loosen and tighten one bolt after another, but you can make very fine adjustments with the system, albeit slightly fiddley.  I suggest a hard cover book and a bubble level app on your phone op top of the saddle to determine your saddle angle.  

I haven't had any issues with the saddle tilt changing as I ride or saddle sliding back and forth on the rails once I tighten to 5NM.  The spec on the bolts are for 8NM, but wasn't sure that was required as I haven't had issues with 5.  

It comes with an extra set of clamps to accommodate for carbon rails, but I'm not sure if the torque specs are different on those as I have cromoly rails on my bike.  

I'd suggest this for anyone trying to take a bit of the edge off of the rear end vibrations.  You can do a lot with tire selection, but some bikes only take 25mm tires, so this could give you a bit more vibration damping for the rear.  If you need significant vibration damping, I'd look elsewhere like a pnw suspension dropper, Cane Creek eeSilk, RedShift's ShockStop, Canyon VCLS, and etc.  The Easton EC70 only helps to slightly lessen the vibration on pavement/road chatter, not gravel or harsh potholes.  

Overall, if you're looking for a product to make your ride significantly more comfortable, look elsewhere(tires, saddle, shoes, bike fit, bar tape, etc).  But if you already went through all those things and you're looking for a slight improvement in vibrations and a small weight saving, a carbon seatpost may be a good solution, and this particular one is pretty good.
review.name: Comfortable and Easy

name: EC70 Seatpost

review.reviewBody: I cannot find a parts list anywhere for the Saris mag trainer. The rest of the unit looks great and works ok. The 9703t Mag remote shifter ratchet won’t hold. I’m told to return whole unit under warranty when a replacement part would do the job fine. Very wasteful.
review.name: Faulty mag trainer ratchet, won’t hold.

review.reviewBody:
I generally dislike indoor training, and much rather go out for a ride and train outside. I purchased this inexpensive model as I needed for warm sessions at races (just got to try racing). The setup was relatively quick given there was some assembly required. It is also of solid construction and very stable when setup correctly. However, upon first setup I noticed the trainer was not working properly, mainly due to lack to attention to detail - allow me to explain.

- Following the setup instructions would end up with a setup of LOWEST resistance of the magnetic adjuster, when the shifter is at the HIGHEST setting. So trying to decrease the resistance, or even increase it, with the control lever is to no avail. The solution is to set the manual resistance knob to the HIGHEST resistance level once the cable has been routed. I let Saris support know of this needed update to their instructions.
- Another shortcoming was that the remote control lever did not have enough resistance to hold the LOWEST resistance setting when the cable has the most tension. The tension on the cable would just pull on the lever back to the highest setting. I initially thought I have gotten a workout controller, but it was sealed new when I unpacked it. I took on disassembling the controller and inspection the internal mechanism. It is a very simple ratcheting mechanism with bi-directional pawl. Although all made of plastic, everything was in good condition and looked new. The pawl is kept in place by means of a an arc shape that springs out and keeps tension on the ratchet teeth. There is just not enough tension on the pawl to counter the tension from the cable. I solved by inserting a piece of rubber under the pawl arc. 

The trainer works like a charm after these adjustments.

Also, pay attention to the hidden feature of the rubber feet to stabilize the trainer on uneven surfaces, it would otherwise wobble. The instructions explain their use.
review.name: Excellent product at a  value price, but...

review.reviewBody: A great trainer with a great price. I've used it daily for four months and nary a problem.
review.name: What's Not To Like!

review.reviewBody: Still putting together the Mag+. Will review after use
review.name: Saris - Mag+ Trainer-Ricardo

review.reviewBody: I got my trainer about a month and a half ago, and it works great. It's sturdy, holds the bike tight with the provided rear axle, has good resistance, and is actually relatively quiet on a solid floor. My only advice would be to not spend the extra money for the handlebar cable to change resistances. I did this, and found that it works very poorly, I took it off my trainer right after trying it out. I find the trainer performs best when I set the resistance at the highest setting and simply change gears as normal to vary my effort. Overall works great for inside spinning.
review.name: Great for winter spinning

review.reviewBody: I purchased the mag+trainer after  hip surgery it is the best investment to keep riding over the winter and help with my recovery!
review.name: EXCELLENT PRODUCT

review.reviewBody: I have had this trainer for a few months now and have already put several hundred miles on it with no issues. Does the needed job for inside training rides at a reasonable price.
review.name: Mag+ Trainer Does the Job Needed

review.reviewBody: Lo tengo hace cinco años. Lo ocupo todos los años durante los meses más fríos (3 o 4). Para mí funciona perfectamente. Es bastante simple y silencioso. Si bien la resistencia que opone no es mucha, se puede graduar bastante con los cambios de la bicicleta. Ante todo hay que considerar que pertenece a la gama baja de rodillos del fabricante (bajo precio y bajas prestaciones).

review.reviewBody: I love the trainer. I set it up in the basement during this long cold winter when even walking outside is no fun. This provided me safe and consistent exercise. When spring does come I'll be ready to get out and enjoy it.

review.reviewBody: The 45L outdoor backpack has now become my go-to everyday carry bag. It's spacious but doesn't feel big (I'm 5'10). The straps are comfy, and comfy enough that I didn't need to keep the waist belt on -- removing the waist belt also lessens the bulk of the bag! All the cord loop system is great, I love love it ! I was even to rig the old PD key chain along with the anchor to create a key holder on the backpack strap! The new design for accessing the top of the bag is amazing, super easy to use and now that I've been using it for awhile, its become the best bag access method I've ever tried! And I got this bag along with the 2L outdoor sling and I now can finally attach the sling to the backpack straps which is just pure magic for me!!! If there's one improvement for the next iteration, I would recommend to move the inside pocket onto the outside, just in the kangaroo pouch area so that it's easier to access, but to do a work around for my set up, I transferred the key loop that comes with the bag onto the one of the loops by the kangaroo pouch and attached an old pencil pouch to it :) oh and and the mesh by the backpack straps at first I wouldn't use but now that's where I put my wallet on one and my earpods on the other! TBH BEST BAG EVER IT IS PURE MAGIC!!
review.name: PURE MAGIC!!!

review.reviewBody: I bought this jacket a few months ago for my bike commute to work. Yesterday was the first day I wore it in the rain: it was light rain at about 1mm/hr. My ride is only 8km and takes about 25 mins. I was completely soaked through by about the halfway point. I've had water resistant jackets that kept me drier than this. I don't recommend this jacket for anything more than a short walk in drizzle. It's too bad because the fit and lightness is exactly what I was looking for,
review.name: Not water proof, and barely water resistant

review.reviewBody: I was very excited about this rain jacket because I bike a lot and it's yellow. I got rid of a very expensive and heavy Mountain Hardwear jacket from 25 years ago. Well when it started to rain, I watched the beads on the outside of the jacket  soak right through and then my neck was wet and my arms were wet through the jacket. I wasn't sweating because we were just walking around a park in the rain. I had the pit zips open and it was not warm out. I'm very sad to say that this Mountain Hardware doesn't keep water out at all. It was better than nothing.
review.name: I wore it once in the rain and got wet

review.reviewBody: I bought the jacket to replace my 15 year old Marmot precip in anticipation of a week long backpack trip in the Wind River mountains. I decided to check its weather protection in the shower and learned that it has significant leaks under both arms after only 3 minutes in the shower. Probably the pit zippers. The old Marmot kept me dryer.
review.name: Leaky

review.reviewBody: Bought this jacket about a month ago and have had the opportunity to wear it in the rain. Very light weight but sealed seems and great repelling water. Have bought several things from backcountry and they get it shipped out quickly. Mountain Hardwear makes great apparel and this jacket is no exception.
review.name: Great Jacket and great customer service

review.reviewBody: nice jacket ,i really need and like this one,i will buy it again
review.name: Nice jacket

review.reviewBody: Very comfortable, high quality, light weight rain jacket. Have used it mostly as a wind breaker. Very pleased with the purchase.
review.name: Portable water and wind protection

review.reviewBody: THE most comfortable rain jacket I've had. Basically a thin soft shell jacket with a waterproof membrane. Build quality is top-notch, and the face fabric is soft and stretchy unlike any rain jacket I've tried. So far no durability problem after a full year of use. I've gone through hikes where I had to go off trail through some serious spiky bushes which I thought was gonna destroy the jacket. Checking the jacket after the hike I was unable to find any significant wear. If maintaining and properly washing the jacket one in a while, the jacket also seems to be sufficiently waterproof for most drizzles, but does seem to be more prone to wetting out than other more hardshell-like rain jackets. Get this jacket if you plan on wearing it regularly as a wind-rain shell/soft shell on hikes rather than a dedicated severe weather hard shell.
review.name: THE MOST COMFORTABLE

review.reviewBody: PERFECT!!!!! Light, sturdy...........breathable!!!
review.name: GET IT!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

review.reviewBody: I just received this jacket. I've only worn it in light to medium rain and it seemed to work just fine. It's very comfortable, very light, very packable, and I like the pit ventilation. Planning to take it to hike Hadrian's Wall this spring. Relatively trim fit, not baggy.

review.reviewBody: I bought this jacket as an alternative to the more expensive Tungsten II. Fit is big around the hips and a little sloppy around the neck making the jacket run a bit high and slide backwards snug against the face. However, on the plus side, the jacket is warm, dry, light, and entirely waterproof. The thickness and durability of the Ventia fabric is a little bit lighter, thinner, and less durable than the Gore-Tex pro that is on the Tungsten II jacket. Overall, it’s a very nice, lesser expensive alternative to the expensive Tungsten II. Pro tip, jacket runs big, so if you are between sizes, go with the smaller option. Jacket will definitely keep you warm and dry on the slopes and in really crappy cold, wet Seattle winter conditions.

I love my Women’s Snowcrew Jacket. It has great features. It’s warm, wind resistant, moisture resistant, has great pit vents for when it’s warmer out or I’m skiing hard. Overall it’s a great looking and great feeling jacket. I highly recommend it. I also bought the matching Snowcrew pants, and I love them too!
review.name: Women’s Snowcrew Jacket

review.reviewBody: So many excellent features! Can't wait to use this when the snow falls again!

review.reviewBody: Jacket fits TTS - I’m 5-6 130 and the small was perfect length and width. Wore it skiing in all types of wx and was comfortable with just a light fleece underneath. Only thing I would change is the zipper, not sure how long it will last.  It’s flimsy.

review.reviewBody: My jacket is warm and I like how long the back is. The zipper is a bit sticky, but that seemed to be common in the other reviews I read before purchasing. I also love how bright and visible my jacket is.

review.reviewBody: I purchased the same jacket twice! I love this ski jacket. the long tail is perfect on cold days. The vents are great when you need to cool down. On storm days the hood fits perfectly over my helmet.
review.name: Perfect ski jacket

review.reviewBody: What can I say, this jacket is perfect. Very comfortable, I get lots of compliments on it, and it's blocks icy wind better than described/expected. So far, I have needed to lose layers each time because I'm overheated!
review.name: Amazing fit and much warmer than expected!

review.reviewBody: This is an excellent coat. The wind/snow proof features are very comfortable. The material is high quality. The zipper is a bit difficult, but this is due to the weatherproof style of zipper. The teeth are covered by a strip of plastic material to prevent snow and ice buildup. It's loosened up the longer I've used it. It feels a little large for the size I normally wear, it's still completely warm and comfortable with no uncomfortable wind or weather, the extra space will allow me to layer easily. My only CON is that the main exterior pockets are unusually small.
review.name: Best Winter Jacket

review.reviewBody: I love how comfortable these things are. The insole is so cushy and supportive, the shoes are warm, the toebox is big enough to let my feet relax and breathe after a long day of skiing or hiking. I like to support Teva as a brand based on their origin and how they fit my feet. However, the durability is not great and they are not the easiest to get on. I appreciate Teva making a well fitting shoes that isn't too loose and doesn't flip-flop around when walking, but you really have to jam your foot in there especially when breaking the shoes in. The front loop is too small to fit even my pinky finger through it, so it's hard to use the front loop as leverage. The back loop is appropriately sized. The tread of the sole should be extended further up on the heel than it is, like they did for the toe. As a result, I have had these shoes for less than three months with very few actual miles walked in them, and the sole is already splitting from the back of the shoes. I fear these shoes are more appropriate for minimally walking around a campsite, rather than on actual walking surfaces like to dinner or evening refreshments. The front loop is whatever, I can get the shoes on. But I fear the lifespan of the shoe is limited. The good news for Teva is these should both be really easy fixes for the next model of this style of shoe! If these shoes were $20-40 that would be more tolerable, but they aren't. I would return these to the site I bought them from if this problem arose within the return window.
review.name: Very comfortable, not very durable

review.reviewBody: I hike and go to Europe a lot!!! I'm 75 years old and my feet do not like cobblestone streets!!! When I read about the wide toe bed, I was very interested!!! I'm so glad I went that extra step and ordered a pair!!! Just came back from Eastern Europe and walking 19000 steps per day!!! Went to my podiatrist to check on my feet and he was stunned how great they looked!!! I knew it all along and that's why I bought the mules in every color and then this boot!!! I hope you are manufacturing more because all these people were disappointed you were sold out of all the colors!!! Guess I will have to lock mine up!!! And my podiatrist said he was going to get them for his wife and himself!!! Also recommend to his patients!!! When I love something this great, I don't keep it a secret!!!❤️
review.name: I would buy this again and again!!!

review.reviewBody: Reference: 6'4". 240lbs. I wear a US 14EE. Tend to have a rather large gait that gives me terrible posture. Spend a lot of time in the woods, hiking and avoiding nosey people with cameras. A lot of people know me as "Bigfoot;" or to my hermanos in the Northwest US, "Sasquatch." I prefer Mike. But I guess there are a lot of Mikes.... Anyway. I have large feet that never fit in anything. Sneakers, boots, shoes, sandals. I prefer going barefoot most of the time WHICH sucks. Barefoot big feet get cold, man. I was a bit worried with some of the reviews. "Really, tight..." "couldn't get my foot in..." First couple of times I wore them, the opening was a little tight. But it stretched out and fits excellently now. Usually wear these in my cave; but I have taken them on a trek or two whenever the pup needs to take a venture to the outdoors. I don't know if I'd take these for a hike-even with the gripped sole. I'll stick to barefoot for that and warm up with these bad boys.
review.name: Big ol' foot got a warm and toasty foot.

review.reviewBody: So far the Reember Terrian Mid has been a positive experience Definitely go up if you take a 1/2 size. The opening of the shoe was just use the loops provided on the shoe to get them on, definitely not slip on. Overall I'm happy Ty

review.reviewBody: Loved the Reember with the zipper. Best shoe I've ever worn. No zipper - very user unfriendly. Despite using a shoe horn, I can't get it on my foot. Very disappointing!
review.name: Terrible disappointment

review.reviewBody: I wear 13 Wide but this shoe in size 14 fit perfectly snug in the rear with the width and toe space I like in the front. The materials are all weather and sturdy even though the pair is light. Perfect for your suitcase.
review.name: Absolutely perfect

review.reviewBody: Sent these back THREE times just trying to get the correct size. They run WAAAYYY too small. The cuff (foot-hole) is ridiculously tight. Like, to the point that you can't even get your foot in. On the plus side, they "seem" to be well made, minus the weird fabrbric around the outer sole... that does not seem as if it would last very long, especially at the price point. I expect much, much more. The footbed is the ONLY reason I keep attempting to get a pair that actually fit. On a whole, a very miserable experience. Do not recommend unless you are trying them on in person.
review.name: If this next pair do not fit, I'll never buy Teva's again.

review.reviewBody: I got these shoes as a gift two months ago but have only worn them a handful of times for low impact activities such as walking to class and I am already notice wear on the back woven part that attaches to the sole of the shoe. There is even a hole forming in one of the sides where I feel like the sole could start to come off and become a flap. I am really disappointed because I think these shoes are so cute and comfortable but, they already look like they are ruined from just a few wears.

The only thing I feel like needs to be said is SIZE UP. I’m in between a 7.5/8, and when reading reviews, most people said they were TTS or to size down, so I went with the 7.5. I can get them on my feet, but they’re not comfortable at all, and I certainly wouldn’t be able to wear proper hiking socks with them. I’m returning and getting the 8.5.

review.itemreviewed: Lennox Hiker Stkd WP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I am so sad to be writing this review! I wanted to love these shoes but on first outing breaking them in they nearly broke my feet! I have a pair of hiking boots that I love, but they are not waterproof, so I bought these to play that role and can say they are adequately waterproof and the tread performs well on slippery rocks and mud. However, other reviews claimed these boots were too narrow in the toe and wide in the heel and I am sorry to report this is very true! (Sorel, why are all your toes too narrow? I almost always have to size up because of this and this is a frequent complaint in your reviews). For this shoe I went true to size based on recommendations of other reviewers in an attempt to compensate for the narrow toe/too wide heel. But alas, it was not enough. I took them on an inaugural hike yesterday and have giant blisters on both heels despite wearing my thickest socks. Also, my toes are in a lot of pain from the tightness. They did not instantly feel this way upon donning the shoes, and walking around on level ground felt fine and comfortable. But the faults of this shoe were exacerbated by ups and downs on the trail. I had to cut my hike short due to the pain. Because of the awkward fit, sizing up or down is not an option. I am so sad to be returning these boots. review.reviewBody: Very comfortable fit.  #1 on the Virginia Tech safety scale.  Nicely adjustable.  Good ventilation and aerodynamics.  Compared against other top helmets.  This one is more and more easily adjustable than the Lazer, though not as light.  Liked it just a hair better than the Specialized.  Slightly more expensive than those alternatives.
review.name: Excellent all-round helmet

review.reviewBody: The helmet is light and airy, not much for wind noise. The inner harness pinches the back of my head at the top edge of the ratchet strap (may be residual swelling from last crash that made me need a new helmet), but I notice it less each ride. There is an inner fit adjustment on the inside that helps a lot for accomodating head shape. Came from a Smith Trace MIPS that very likely saved my life to the top-rated safety of this Giro. Loved that helmet too.
review.name: Great airflow

review.reviewBody:
I don't think I can endorse this helmet more strongly.  At the same time I was turning left, a car decided to pass me on my left (in a no passing zone of course).  I was flipped up on the hood and "starred" the windshield of the car with my helmet and head.  Other than a solid concussion I didn't have any significant brain injury.  With a less quality helmet I'm not sure I would have had the same outcome.  I purchased it because of its ranking on the VT website.  I recommend reviewing the Virginia Tech helmet rankings prior to purchasing helmets.  

Stay safe out there.
review.name: Got hit by a car wearing it

review.reviewBody: Not too much to say. I like the look of it. It's comfy and easy to adjust. There's also a red flashing light that you can get (not included) that fits into the rear of the helmet, which is a nice bonus safety feature.
review.name: Great, nice looking helmet

review.reviewBody: Lightweight, highly ventilated, comfortable, fits great. But they didn't design the vents in such a way that sunglasses stay in place when you want to slot them in to the holes. I've tried it with several different glasses and they fall out if you shake your head at all or if you bend over to get a bottle, adjust your shoes, stretch, etc. I've lost sunglasses out of the helmet while riding. It's pretty important to be able to put your glasses somewhere besides your face if they're fogging up or getting sweaty.
review.name: Very nice helmet with a critical flaw

review.reviewBody: The helmet fits great and looks good. The only issue I ran into is the MIPS cage that goes around your head sits low in the back just below the base of my skull so after a while, it can put pressure on that area and can lead to a headache. Think of someone taking their finger and pushing into the back of your skull. After two rides I was able to find the right combination of tightness of the helmet and my glasses location to make it work so the helmet now rides correctly and is supportive.
review.name: Great helmet but be sure it fits your he

review.reviewBody: I really love my new cycling helmet..very pleased and happy I found one that fits perfect for me. It’s very expensive but i highly recommend it. I use mine a lot .
review.name: Aries Spherical Helmet

review.reviewBody: My previous helmet was the Giro Aether, which was damaged in a crash, so I needed a new helmet.  I bought this one because I liked the Aether a lot and the Aries has the best rating in the Virginia Tech testing. It fits very well, is comfortable and ventilates well.  It's pricey but for my money it's worth the price, both from a day to day functional point of view and from a safety point of view
review.name: Comfortable Helmet

review.reviewBody: Two rides in, and I’m very happy with this helmet. It’s incredibly lightweight, well ventilated, and fits great. I tried a couple of different brands/styles looking for va higher end helmet and this just felt right immediately.
review.name: Very happy!

review.reviewBody: The cost was a little prohibitive but I finally jumped when Backcountry had 20% off full priced item.  It's an absolutely gorgeous helmet and so comfortable.  I measured 23 inches and went with medium which was perfect.  I've only worn it for a few spins but in love.
